INSERT INTO `roadmap_dynamics` (`id`, `title`, `description`, `position`, `color`, `sample_link`, `template_link`, `status`, `created`) VALUES
(1, 'Problem/ Solution Fit', '<p>The first goal of entrepreneurship is to find a problem that is worth solving. Your proposed solution is your product or service. You must be able to summarize the problem in a single concise sentence. You must also be able to summarize your solution in a single concise sentence. Your initial mission is to validate the value of your solution with the minimal outlay of money, effort and time. After you validate the value of your offering to your target customers, you have achieved problem/solution fit. The most efficient approach to achieve problem/solution fit, is to create the minimum viable simulation of your offer that enables an effective market test. You can iterate by adjusting the solution or changing the target problem then once again attempt to validate problem/solution fit.</p>\r\n<p>Before iterating with customers, you should conduct secondary market research to find any existing validation of the problem, the best existing solutions, any work arounds and trends that may impact the problem or solution.</p>', 'R2', '#58c517', '1485166257_74204310.0 CBS Problem Solution Fit Blueprint v1.1.pdf', '1485166257_33876710.0 Problem Solution Fit Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:23:14'),
(2, 'Pretotype', '<p>The purpose of pretotyping is to help you ensure you are building the right product. The following defintions are listed on this Google blogspot (<a href="https://googletesting.blogspot.com/2011/08/pretotyping-different-type-of-testing.html" target="_blank">https://googletesting.blogspot.com/2011/08/pretotyping-different-type-of-testing.html</a>):</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Pretotyping is a way to test an idea quickly and inexpensively by creating extremely simplified, mocked or virtual versions of that product to help validate the premise that "If we build it, they will use it."</p>\r\n<p>The more formal definition is:</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Testing the initial appeal and actual usage of a potential new product by simulating its core experience with the smallest possible investment of time and money.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>The term and concept of pretotyping was originally developed by Alberto Savoia in 2009 while he was working at Google as Engineering Director and Innovation Agitator. The web site <a href="http://www.pretotyping.org/" target="_blank">http://www.pretotyping.org/</a> is a hub for those interested in pretotyping. You can also follow Alberto Savoia&rsquo;s work on his blog at <a href="http://pretotyping.blogspot.com/" target="_blank">http://pretotyping.blogspot.com/.</a></p>\r\n<p>One practical example of pretotyping provided by Alberto Savoia is that IBM convened a focus group to validate interest in speech recognition. The focus group were given microphones to test the speech recognition solution but indicated the functionality was not critical. In this focus group, IBM actual used typists behind a curtain to simulate the speech recognition capability which is a good example of pretotyping. Alberto Savoia explains pretotyping in this video <a href="https://youtu.be/7sWnsaYv0u4" target="_blank">https://youtu.be/7sWnsaYv0u4.</a></p>', 'R3', '#58c517', '1485166395_55035220.0 Pretotype.pdf', '1485166395_75665120.0 Pretotyping Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:37:22'),
(3, 'Secondary Research', '<p>Before spending a lot of valuable time, money and effort developing a product or service you should conduct market research to determine if there is a real market need and to understand the competitive requirements to satisfy that need. To manage your costs, you should start with secondary research to determine the key hypotheses for your business model then progress to primary research to validate the metrics for your hypotheses.</p>\r\n<p>Secondary research includes information compiled by various organizations, such as government agencies, industry and trade associations, media sources, libraries, chambers of commerce, etc. This information is usually published on line and in reports, magazines, newspapers, and trade publications.</p>\r\n<p>A lot of information is available free of charge from public sources. In addition, commercial organizations, such as trade associations and Dun &amp; Bradstreet, provide access to research for a fee.</p>\r\n<p>An online key word search will reveal a list of information sources. One useful source is the Statistical Abstract of the United States that includes statistics about social, political and economic conditions in the U.S. The U.S. Industry and Trade Outlook provides financial performance information for U.S. Manufacturers and identifies emerging trends. The U.S. Census Bureau provides valuable market statistics and the U.S. Government Printing Office offers a range of publications on a variety of topics. The Small Business Association (SBA) offers financial assistance and counseling services through Small Business Development Centers (SBDCs), management assistance through programs like SCORE, and low cost publications. The counselors at SCORE can provide free consultation on secondary research. The Encyclopedia of Associations (Gale Research), and the Encyclopedia of Business Information Sources (Gale Group) provide useful information about trade associations. Other useful sources include: &ldquo;ThomasNet&rdquo;, an online resource that connects industrial buyers and sellers, and the &ldquo;Harris InfoSource All-Industries and Manufacturing Directories&rdquo;. These sources can help you research businesses in a particular industry, assess competitors and find manufacturers and suppliers for your product or service. You should also read publications from the trade association for your offering as well as the trade associations for your target market, supply channels and distribution channels.</p>\r\n<p>The goals for your secondary research should include identifying the typical business metrics that you will measure to validate the market opportunity and the determining the hypotheses that validate your business model.</p>\r\n<p><a href="https://www.allbusiness.com/the-difference-between-secondary-and-primary-market-research-1310-1.html" target="_blank">https://www.allbusiness.com/the-difference-between-secondary-and-primary-market-research-1310-1.html</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="https://www.entrepreneur.com/encyclopedia/secondary-market-research" target="_blank">https://www.entrepreneur.com/encyclopedia/secondary-market-research</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/217388 https://www.cleverism.com/market-research-techniques-primary-secondary/" target="_blank">https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/217388 https://www.cleverism.com/market-research-techniques-primary-secondary/</a></p>', 'R1', '#e8a514', '1485166497_16839030.0 CBS Secondary Research.pdf', '1485166497_73454930.0 Secondary Research Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:24:17'),
(4, 'Elevator Pitch', '<p>An elevator pitch is a 30 second summary of your business opportunity. Start your pitch with a "hook" that will pique the interest of your audience. Although you only have 30 seconds, your pitch should achieve the following:</p>\r\n<p>1. Introduce yourself, your team, and key achievements.</p>\r\n<p>2. Describe the target problem and your solution.</p>\r\n<p>3. Describe your target market, its size, your competition and your competitive advantage.</p>\r\n<p>4. Explain how you make money.</p>\r\n<p>5. Summarize the current status of your business.</p>\r\n<p>6. Explain what you want or include a clear call to action.</p>\r\n<p>Your tone should be natural however you should convey high energy and a passion for your business.</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.businessknowhow.com/money/elevator.htm" target="_blank">http://www.businessknowhow.com/money/elevator.htm</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elevator_pitch" target="_blank">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elevator_pitch</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://articles.bplans.com/the-7-key-components-of-a-perfect-elevator-pitch/" target="_blank">http://articles.bplans.com/the-7-key-components-of-a-perfect-elevator-pitch/</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://articles.bplans.com/elevator-pitch-guide/" target="_blank">http://articles.bplans.com/elevator-pitch-guide/</a></p>', 'R4', '#e8a514', '1485166675_58810340.0 CBS Elevator Pitch.pdf', '1485166675_17628040.0 Elevator Pitch Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:37:45'),
(5, 'Engage  Co Founders', '<p>According to Tech Stars, &ldquo;founders are individuals who create, execute, and invest in ideas to turn them into startups&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p>Starting a company is extremely difficult. To increase your probability of success, you need all the help you can get. According to Chris Wilkinson, Head of talent at Forward Partners, it is a good practice to find a genuine peer who can challenge you and support you in equal measure. A co-founder can challenge your assumptions and raise concerns. She will tell you when you are on the wrong path and you will listen. In fact, many successful companies started with a business co-founder and a technical co-founder. To avoid destructive conflict, co-founders should have complementary skill sets and must share core values and the company vision. You should pay your co-founder what she deserves and be generous with equity.</p>\r\n<p>Having a co-founder allows you to share the workload; celebrate the successes together; support each other during challenging times; improve decision making by considering opposing views; leverage each other&rsquo;s experience when making decisions; and assign responsibilities based on relative strengths. The benefits of a co-founder also include the fact that your co-founder may be able to see whatever is obscured by your blind spots, you can be in two different physical locations at the same time, you can brain storm, get a second opinion, and duel with a devil&rsquo;s advocate. The disadvantages of a co-founder include complications caused by having another person involved, and disagreements about the relative value of each other&rsquo;s contributions. However, the main downside is that it is easy to get into a co-founder relationship but it is very difficult to get out.</p>\r\n<p>When selecting a co-founder, you should figure out which competencies you need to succeed and which can accelerate your success. You should then determine which of these competencies you cannot provide. Next, you should determine which of the gap competencies you can learn, which can be acquired and which are best provided by a co-founder. This will help you determine what to look for in a co-founder. However, a common vision, common moral and ethical standards and chemistry must trump all else.</p>\r\n<p>You and your co-founder should determine what each of you will commit in terms of time, funds, technology, experience and what you expect to achieve together, such as a preferred exit strategy.</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://jacquesmattheij.com/why-you-should-or-should-not-get-a-co-founder" target="_blank">http://jacquesmattheij.com/why-you-should-or-should-not-get-a-co-founder</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.foxbusiness.com/features/2014/02/19/4-advantages-to-starting-up-with-co-founder.html" target="_blank">http://www.foxbusiness.com/features/2014/02/19/4-advantages-to-starting-up-with-co-founder.html</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.forwardpartners.com/blog/hiring-a-co-founder/" target="_blank">http://www.forwardpartners.com/blog/hiring-a-co-founder/</a></p>', 'R2', '#58c517', '1485166779_93873550.0 CBS Engage Co-Founders.pdf', '1485166779_25585350.0 Co Founder Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:25:03'),
(6, 'Distribution Strategy', '<p>Distribution is the process of making your offerings available to your customers. You need to decide the most effective approach to service your customers. You can sell directly to your customers or through a distribution channel. For example, you can sell your virtual reality headset directly to customers via your online store or sell through companies like Amazon.</p>\r\n<p>Your distribution strategy must be consistent with the other elements of you marketing approach including your product, price, and promotion. For example, you probably shouldn&rsquo;t distribute a high end product through a channel that targets low income customers. Or try to sell a low price product through a high end channel. However, coordinated promotions with your selected distribution channel could improve the return on you marketing efforts.</p>\r\n<p>Distribution can be a competitive advantage if it elevates your customer value over their other options. For example, your distribution channel may enhance customer convenience by making your offering available on a shelf next to complementary offerings that the customer perceives as the total solution. However, distribution can also have a downside because you can lose control of the customer, there may be a high distribution cost and your competitors may have a better arrangement with your distribution channel.</p>\r\n<p>According to MaRS Library, your distribution strategy combines three channels and you should consider five key factors when selecting a distribution channel:</p>\r\n<p>Channels:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Sales</li>\r\n<li>Delivery</li>\r\n<li>Service</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><a href="https://www.marsdd.com/mars-library/distribution/" target="">https://www.marsdd.com/mars-library/distribution/</a></p>\r\n<p>For each of these channels your solution may be direct, via a third party or a combination of both. For example, you may use independent third party sales reps but ship your products directly to customers. You also may provide direct customer service.</p>\r\n<p>When selecting a distribution channel, you should consider the following:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Size and distribution of each target market segment.</li>\r\n<li>Distribution costs which can be 5% to 70% of the price.</li>\r\n<li>Whether it is easy for your channel to sell your offering or if training is required.</li>\r\n<li>How much control you will have over customer access.</li>\r\n<li>Whether the distribution arrangement is flexible for you. For, example your arrangement may be exclusive, you may have to pay in advance for shelf space and you may be locked into meeting the costs of returns and unsold inventory.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>You may need a different distribution strategy for your different target markets, such as consumers versus business users. You must also consider the customer relationship that you desire with each target market. For example, the Business Model Canvas considers the following customer relationships; personal assistance, self-service, knowledge-sharing communities, and co-creation where customers have input to your offerings. You must be able to develop and sustain the customer relationship that you select for each target market. In addition, your selected customer relationship must be consistent with the distribution channel for each target market.</p>\r\n<p>When selecting a customer relationship, you should consider the complexity of your solution and the complexity of your marketing strategy. For example, some business solutions have complex selling cycles, have a complex installation process and require substantial training for users. Simple, low cost solutions may not have the margins to support complex marketing plans. Conversely, a complex offering is unlikely to succeed if the marketing approach is simplistic and under financed.</p>\r\n<p>If your offering has strong brand recognition, then you might consider a push marketing strategy where you advertise your offerings but the customers buy through your distribution channel. If your brand loyalty is low, then you may have to co-fund promotional activities with your distribution channel.</p>', 'R3', '#58c517', '1485166828_79177260.0 CBS Distribution Strategy.pdf', '1485166828_62412460.0 Distribution Strategy Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:38:14'),
(7, 'Business Model Canvas', '<p>A business model is the essence of how an organization creates, delivers and captures value. Companies organize their supply channels to feed the development of their offerings. They also organize their distribution channels to deliver their offerings to their target customers. Finally, they have to convince their customers that the value provided by their offerings warrant a reward, such as a payment for your services rendered. The organization&rsquo;s success also depends on a number of stakeholders who contribute to the organization&rsquo;s value chain. The business model must clarify the value added by each of these key stakeholders.</p>\r\n<p>The purpose of a business model framework is to facilitate the design and documentation of a company''s business model. The Business Model Canvas is a popular business model framework that was invented by Alexander Osterwalder and Yves Pigneur. It is a visual chart comprised of the key elements of an organization&rsquo;s value chain. These elements include:</p>\r\n<p><strong>Customer Segments</strong> that have different needs and attributes that define how they should be served.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Value Proposition</strong> which is the set of benefits that are valued by the target customers and provided by the company&rsquo;s offerings.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Revenue Streams</strong> define how the company makes money from each customer segment.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Customer</strong> Relationships define how the company wants to interoperate with its customers, such as personal assistance, self-service, knowledge-sharing communities, and co-creation where customers have input to the company&rsquo;s offerings.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Channels</strong> are used to distribute a company&rsquo;s value to its customers in a fast, efficient and cost effective manner.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Key Activities</strong> required to execute a company''s business model and deliver its value proposition.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Key Resources</strong> necessary to create and maintain customer value.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Partner Network</strong> comprised of complementary business alliances that enable the company to focus on its core competency.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Cost Structure</strong> defines the key cost drivers that enable the company to create customer value.</p>\r\n<p>A business model framework is a simple way for a startup to visualize its business model and quickly assess potential trade-offs before they pivot. Writing a detailed business plan during the seed stage of a startup makes less sense because of extreme uncertainty and the need to quickly refine the business model during the lean startup learning process. A detailed business plan makes more sense after the company validates its business model.</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.businessmodelgeneration.com/canvas/bmc" target="_blank">http://www.businessmodelgeneration.com/canvas/bmc</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Business_Model_Canvas" target="_blank">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Business_Model_Canvas</a></p>', 'R1', '#e8a514', '1485166955_21618870.0 CBS Business Model Canvas.pdf', '1485166955_69454870.0 Business Model Canvas Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:25:43'),
(8, 'IP Strategy', '<p>The main forms for intellectual property that entrepreneurs can use as a risk reduction strategy include:</p>\r\n<p>Domain names represent virtual locations on the Internet where entrepreneurs can locate their web site. You can purchase a domain for your dedicated use which reduces the risk that competitors can cause confusion by preventing them from using the same domain name.</p>\r\n<p>Copyright gives the creator of an original work exclusive rights to it, usually for a limited time. Copyright can apply to a wide range of creative, intellectual, or artistic forms, or "works". Copyright does not cover ideas and information, only the form or manner in which they are expressed.</p>\r\n<p>Trademarks are a recognizable sign, design or expression which distinguishes products or services of a particular company from the similar products or services of other companies. Entrepreneurs can use trademarks to reduce the risk that competitors will impinge on their brand identity.</p>\r\n<p>Patents are a right granted by a government to an inventor, that excludes others from making, using, selling, offering to sell, or importing the same invention for a limited period of time, in exchange for the public disclosure of the invention. This can be a significant risk reduction strategy for an entrepreneur if the patent can be defended against infringers. However, competitors have many ways to work around a patent. For this reason, patents often have more value as a negotiation tool than an exclusionary barrier. In general, a patent application must fulfil three main requirements: it has to be new, not obvious and there needs to be a useful industrial application. If an entrepreneur perceives that the disclosure of key information to potential investors and business partners during a discussion will increase risk then she can file a provisional patent application to register the filing date of the invention. The entrepreneur will then have 12 months to have discussions and validate their business model before she must file a full patent application to protect the invention.</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.wipo.int/about-ip/en/" target="_blank">http://www.wipo.int/about-ip/en/</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intellectual_property" target="_blank">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intellectual_property</a></p>', 'R4', '#e8a514', '1485167040_16615580.0 CBS IP Strategy.pdf', '1485167040_25866880.0 IP Strategy Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:38:32'),
(9, 'Landing Page', '<p>A landing page is a stand-alone web page that is designed to achieve a specific objective which usually includes Click Throughs or Lead Generation. The web page includes basic information about the startup designed to generate sufficient interest for the visitor to respond. The types of prospects who respond, the volume of responses and information submitted by the prospects should inform different components of the company&rsquo;s business model.</p>\r\n<p>A landing page is a low cost method to generate feedback directly from prospects. A startup can use this feedback to reduce uncertainty. However, for this process to be effective, the startup should have at least one predetermined hypothesis that the responses should prove or reject. Alternatively, generating leads will create a mailing list of motivated prospects for your subsequent marketing and sales campaigns.</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://unbounce.com/landing-page-articles/what-is-a-landing-page/" target="_blank">http://unbounce.com/landing-page-articles/what-is-a-landing-page/</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://thelandingpagecourse.com/landing-page-101-intro/" target="_blank">http://thelandingpagecourse.com/landing-page-101-intro/</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Landing_page" target="_blank">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Landing_page</a></p>', 'R2', '#58c517', '1485167264_76669790.0 CBS Landing Page.pdf', '1485167264_18678990.0 Landing Page Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:26:01'),
(10, 'MVP Front End', '<p>Developing a full product before testing a concept in the market is a risky proposition due to the extreme uncertainty associated with startup operations. Startups need the opportunity to learn while validating their vision; ambiguity must be replaced by increasing certainty over the shortest possible timeframe.</p>\r\n<p>A startup believes its offering will solve an important problem faced by its target market. The founders often expect that their offering will deliver an unprecedented return on their investment. This belief includes two important assumptions: the value hypothesis and the growth hypothesis.</p>\r\n<p>For a startup, it is essential to validate its value and growth hypotheses as soon as possible. In order to do this, you have to develop a representation of your product that is minimal but enables customers to visualize its value. The lean startup philosophy advocates the efficient use of resources by introducing a minimum viable product (MVP) to the market as soon as possible in order to test its value and market potential. This allows customers to experience the value of your offerings and enables you to determine what is valuable. This will enable you to release the right product in the right market. The company then needs to design experiments that will use the MVP to confirm (or refute) its value and growth hypotheses. MVP experiments should also track metrics related to lifetime value and customer acquisition costs.</p>\r\n<p>A minimum viable product (MVP) is the minimum set of features that provide the minimum acceptable value for the early adopters. It accelerates the team&rsquo;s ability to collect the maximum amount of validated learning about customers with the minimal development effort. You should use your MVP to test one or more fundamental business hypotheses that inform critical components of your business model. If used effectively, the MVP will help you learn whether to proceed, pivot or stop. According to Steve Blank "You&rsquo;re selling the vision and delivering the minimum feature set to visionaries, not everyone&rdquo;. Gathering insights from an MVP is often less expensive than using a product with more features that would increase costs and risk if the product fails due to incorrect assumptions. The term MVP was coined and defined by Frank Robinson, and popularized by Steve Blank, and Eric Ries.</p>\r\n<p>As part of the strategy to deploy first then code later, you can build a dummy version of the MVP to validate the minimum feature set prior to building the MVP. This MVP front end allows selected users to visualize the MVP&rsquo;s features and navigation with dummy data. This allows you to generate and process feedback from early adopters then iterate prior to building the full MVP. This is consistent with Steve Blank''s customer development methodology that focuses on continual product iteration and refinement based on customer feedback.</p>\r\n<p>Ries, Eric (August 3, 2009). "Minimum Viable Product: a guide".</p>\r\n<p>Blank, Steve (March 4, 2010). "Perfection By Subtraction &ndash; The Minimum Feature Set".</p>\r\n<p><a target="_blank">http://timreview.ca/article/535</a></p>', 'R3', '#58c517', '1485167396_542148100.0 CBS MVP Front End.pdf', '1485167396_257899100.0 MVP Front End Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:39:14'),
(11, 'Explainer Video', '<p>An explainer video is a great tool to communicate a complex message, such as your business model, in a simple way. First you should identify the purpose of the video, its target audience, the key message and a call to action. You should then write, review and approve the script. Then record, correct and approve the audio. Then you should produce, correct and approve the video. One approach for the content is:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Introduce a character to capture interest. The main character should represent the audience, such as a customer.</li>\r\n<li>Introduce the problem statement and emphasize the pain.</li>\r\n<li>Introduce the solution</li>\r\n<li>Explain your business model and its rationale</li>\r\n<li>Summarize the benefits of your solution to your target audience</li>\r\n<li>Conclude the video with a call to action</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Use interesting visuals, make it upbeat, and add a little humor. The script should be about 200 words and the video should be approximately 30 to 90 minutes.</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/03/13/explainer-videos" target="_blank">http://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/03/13/explainer-videos</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.videobrewery.com/blog/10-best-startup-explainer-videos-ever" target="_blank">http://www.videobrewery.com/blog/10-best-startup-explainer-videos-ever</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.switchvideo.com/resources/the-best-explainer-videos/" target="_blank">http://www.switchvideo.com/resources/the-best-explainer-videos/</a></p>', 'R1', '#e8a514', '1485167468_98384110.0 CBS Explainer Video.pdf', '1485167468_644639110.0 Explainer Video Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:26:21'),
(12, 'Primary Market Research', '<p>The purpose of primary market research is to gather information directly from your target market that proves or disproves one or more hypotheses. Your Landing page, MVP front end and your MVP are key tools that enable you to conduct primary research.</p>\r\n<p>You have three main methods to conduct primary market research: surveys and questionnaires, interviews, and focus groups. Before creating survey questions, it is necessary to design your research questions to clarify the business goals that the survey will address. Surveys are sent through the mail, in email, or are conducted through Web-based services.</p>\r\n<p>There are generally two ways to gather information through interviews from experienced individuals in a relevant industry and from individuals within a target profile. A focus group, for instance, may be used to test the appeal and taste of a new food product in comparison to a competing product, or to test the usability of a new computer game. After participants observe your demonstration or presentation, you can collect feedback through group discussion, from individual verbal question and answer sessions, or from a written questionnaire or survey.</p>\r\n<p>Quantitative research is numerically-based and obtains the hard numbers that allow you to make confident decisions. Qualitative information is a primary form of market research which focuses on consumer feelings and opinions about your offering. Qualitative research highlights the facts and figures collected through quantitative research. By speaking at length with small groups of 8-10 people, more insightful questions can be asked regarding brands and new product developments. Depth interviews involve a researcher accompanying the consumer while they consume your offering. You can use sampling to get responses from a representative group of customers whose opinions are likely to reflect the opinions of the broader customer base.</p>\r\n<p>When conducting primary market research, you can gather two basic types of information: exploratory or specific. Exploratory research is open-ended, helps you define a specific problem, and usually involves detailed, unstructured interviews in which lengthy answers are solicited from a small group of respondents. Specific research, on the other hand, is precise in scope and is used to solve a problem that has been identified by your exploratory research. Your interviews should be structured and formal in approach.</p>\r\n<p><a href="https://www.entrepreneur.com/encyclopedia/primary-market-research" target="_blank">https://www.entrepreneur.com/encyclopedia/primary-market-research</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://businesscasestudies.co.uk/jd-sports/using-market-research-to-support-decision-making/primary-market-research.html#ixzz47OB8Kx8w" target="_blank">http://businesscasestudies.co.uk/jd-sports/using-market-research-to-support-decision-making/primary-market-research.html#ixzz47OB8Kx8w</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://businesscasestudies.co.uk/jd-sports/using-market-research-to-support-decision-making/primary-market-research.html#ixzz47OAlzAmh" target="_blank">http://businesscasestudies.co.uk/jd-sports/using-market-research-to-support-decision-making/primary-market-research.html#ixzz47OAlzAmh</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://businesscasestudies.co.uk/jd-sports/using-market-research-to-support-decision-making/primary-market-research.html#ixzz47OAb2MXq" target="_blank">http://businesscasestudies.co.uk/jd-sports/using-market-research-to-support-decision-making/primary-market-research.html#ixzz47OAb2MXq</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://businesscasestudies.co.uk/jd-sports/using-market-research-to-support-decision-making/primary-market-research.html#ixzz47OA0vmXw" target="_blank">http://businesscasestudies.co.uk/jd-sports/using-market-research-to-support-decision-making/primary-market-research.html#ixzz47OA0vmXw</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://businesscasestudies.co.uk/jd-sports/using-market-research-to-support-decision-making/primary-market-research.html#ixzz47O9YlRgX" target="_blank">http://businesscasestudies.co.uk/jd-sports/using-market-research-to-support-decision-making/primary-market-research.html#ixzz47O9YlRgX</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://smallbusiness.findlaw.com/business-operations/how-to-conduct-primary-market-research-for-your-small-business.html#sthash.9VcgyCWW.dpuf" target="_blank">http://smallbusiness.findlaw.com/business-operations/how-to-conduct-primary-market-research-for-your-small-business.html#sthash.9VcgyCWW.dpuf</a></p>', 'R4', '#e8a514', '1485167517_294252120.0 CBS Primary Research.pdf', '1485167517_702516120.0 Primary Research Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:39:31'),
(13, 'Product/ Market Fit', '<p>According to Andrew Chen, you have achieved product/market fit when people who know they want your product are happy with what you''re offering. The term has been attributed to Marc Andreessen:</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://web.stanford.edu/class/ee204/ProductMarketFit.html" target="_blank">http://web.stanford.edu/class/ee204/ProductMarketFit.html</a></p>\r\n<p>To achieve product market fit you must develop an offering that customers demand then validate that your business model is able to satisfy that demand while meeting your business objectives. As you iterate the problem and the solution, you must iterate the business model to ensure it is repeatable and scalable. A minimal viable product that has been honed by multiple iterations will enable you to validate market and industry value. When your offering is too good for your target customer to refuse and your business model extracts sufficient value for you to continue attracting customers then you have achieved product/market fit. At that time, your existing customers are happy enough to refer your offering and you will have developed a sustainable and repeatable business model to attract more users and also convert them into happy, active, paying advocates.</p>\r\n<p>Your customers must have a compelling reason to buy because they see the clear cost/benefit value, it must be easy to understand, easy to acquire, easy to adopt, easy to use, easy to adjust, easy to maintain and easy for customers to explain to other customers. If any of these are too complex, then your product will not fly off the shelf. Similarly, if your business model cannot deliver this customer value in a sustainable way then a competitor or new entrant will beat you to product/market fit. To improve customer retention, your offering should be difficult for your customer to stop using and should have increasing value over time. For example, your offering will have these characteristics if it has very strong network effects.</p>\r\n<p>After you achieve product/market fit, your next mission is to scale the business. This is the best time to raise money which you will use to fuel your growth engine.</p>\r\n<p><a href="https://www.quora.com/How-do-you-define-Product-Market-Fit" target="_blank">https://www.quora.com/How-do-you-define-Product-Market-Fit</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://web.archive.org/web/20070701074943/http://blog.pmarca.com/2007/06/the-pmarca-gu-2.html" target="_blank">http://web.archive.org/web/20070701074943/http://blog.pmarca.com/2007/06/the-pmarca-gu-2.html</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="https://leanstack.com/achievingproductmarketfit/" target="_blank">https://leanstack.com/achievingproductmarketfit/</a></p>', 'R2', '#58c517', '1485167555_255631130.0 CBS Product Market Fit.pdf', '1485167555_161145130.0 Product Market Fit Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:27:34'),
(14, 'Market Entry Strategy', '<p>If your offering is an incremental improvement over other offerings and does not demand a significant change in customer behavior, then you can apply the standard market entry strategies proposed in the technology adoption lifecycle. This describes the adoption of a new offering, according to the demographic and psychological characteristics of a defined adopter group. The process of adoption over time is typically illustrated as a classical normal distribution or "bell curve". The model indicates that the first group of people to use a new product is called "innovators," followed by "early adopters". Next come the &ldquo;early majority&rdquo; and &ldquo;late majority&rdquo;, and the last group to eventually adopt a product are called "laggards".</p>\r\n<p>Conversely, if your offering is disruptive or a discontinuous innovation, then you should prioritize the need for market development activities over a standard market penetration approach. In his book &lsquo;Crossing the Chasm&rsquo;, Geoffrey Moore recognizes the same five main market segments namely innovators, early adopters, early majority, late majority and laggards. However, he believes each of these segments have very different expectations that demand a different &ldquo;whole product&rdquo;, marketing strategy, distribution approach, sales strategy and pricing plan. The whole product is a &ldquo;core product&rdquo; augmented by everything that is needed for the customer to have a compelling reason to buy. For example, innovators are generally happy with the core product even if it has deficiencies. Whereas pragmatists demand maintenance and other complementary offerings that augment the core product.</p>\r\n<p>According to Moore, a startup should focus on one group of customers at a time, using each group as a base for marketing to the next group in sequence. The most difficult step is making the transition between visionaries (e.g., early adopters) and pragmatists (e.g., early majority). Moore believes the differences between visionaries and pragmatists are so wide that they form a chasm that many startups struggle to cross. One way to cross this chasm is to create a beachhead within a small segment of the early majority and apply overwhelming focus to dominate that sub-segment then scale from there.</p>\r\n<p>In summary, a startup with an innovative offering should select an initial target market to attack. For example, that may be the &ldquo;early adopters&rdquo;. You need to understand their expectations then build an MVP that includes the minimum functionality required to meet their key needs. From there, you should iterate the MVP to deliver the value required to dominate this initial market. Then you should fully understand the expectations of the next target market. This may be the early majority. You should leverage referrals from early adopters. However, you should adjust your offering to ensure it meets the minimum expectations of the early majority. From there you should iterate to deliver the value required to dominate this second market. You can then repeat this process for each successive target market.</p>\r\n<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Technology_adoption_life_cycle" target="_blank">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Technology_adoption_life_cycle</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.ondigitalmarketing.com/learn/odm/foundations/5-customer-segments-technology-adoption/" target="_blank">http://www.ondigitalmarketing.com/learn/odm/foundations/5-customer-segments-technology-adoption/</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="https://www.marsdd.com/mars-library/technology-adoption-lifecycle-talc/" target="_blank">https://www.marsdd.com/mars-library/technology-adoption-lifecycle-talc/</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crossing_the_Chasm" target="_blank">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crossing_the_Chasm</a></p>', 'R3', '#58c517', '1485167705_484418140.0 CBS Market Entry Strategy.pdf', '1485167705_112317140.0 Market Entry Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:39:53'),
(15, 'Startup Team', '<p>According to Tech Stars, the Minimum Viable Team is &ldquo;a group of people able to execute on an idea&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p>Sachin Rekhi makes the argument that a minimum viable team is just big enough to ship and iterate on your minimum viable product. This approach has advantages before you reach product/market fit. The minimum viable team minimizes your cost of communication while the organization is learning rapidly. It also accelerates decision making. The smaller the team the easiest it is to achieve and maintain alignment. Instagram, for example, had a team of only 13 employees and built a service with over 30 million users and sold to Facebook for $1B. Similarly, WhatsApp had 55 employees and grew to over 450M users and sold to Facebook for $19B.</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.sachinrekhi.com/minimum-viable-team" target="_blank">http://www.sachinrekhi.com/minimum-viable-team</a></p>\r\n<p>It is extremely important for your initial team to have chemistry. Startups are complex and often have a thin margin of error. One bad hire can alter your trajectory from marginal success to marginal failure. One way to hire a team that will be on the same page and will stay on the same page is to hire people with an uncompromising belief in your vision and mission. Your goal is to find candidates who have the skills you need but only select those that share your vision and truly believe in your mission.</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.techstars.com/content/uncategorized/how-to-find-your-minimum-viable-team-mvt/" target="_blank">http://www.techstars.com/content/uncategorized/how-to-find-your-minimum-viable-team-mvt/</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://techstars.com/uploads/ugb_uploads/2013/03/Co-Founder-Development-MVT.pdf" target="_blank">http://techstars.com/uploads/ugb_uploads/2013/03/Co-Founder-Development-MVT.pdf</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.endeavor.org/network/what-makes-a-minimum-viable-team/" target="_blank">http://www.endeavor.org/network/what-makes-a-minimum-viable-team/</a></p>\r\n<p>According to Charlie O&rsquo;Donnell, in the early stages of a startup you only need the following roles:</p>\r\n<p>1) Manage Outside Stakeholders (Sales, PR, Business Development, Recruitment)</p>\r\n<p>2) Customer Experience</p>\r\n<p>3) Engineering</p>\r\n<p>4) Outsourced functions</p>\r\n<p>Conversely, mature companies can include the following roles:</p>\r\n<p>1) IT/Engineering</p>\r\n<p>2) Marketing</p>\r\n<p>3) Sales</p>\r\n<p>4) Business Development</p>\r\n<p>5) PR</p>\r\n<p>6) Design</p>\r\n<p>7) Product Management</p>\r\n<p>8) HR</p>\r\n<p>9) Operations</p>\r\n<p>10) Finance</p>\r\n<p>11) Legal</p>\r\n<p>12) Purchasing</p>\r\n<p>13) Customer Service</p>\r\n<p>14) Research and Development</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.thisisgoingtobebig.com/blog/2012/8/22/minimum-viable-team.html" target="_blank">http://www.thisisgoingtobebig.com/blog/2012/8/22/minimum-viable-team.html</a></p>', 'R1', '#e8a514', '1485167853_461288150.0 CBS Startup Team.pdf', '1485167853_603536150.0 Startup Team Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:27:56'),
(16, 'Pitch Deck', '<p>A pitch deck is a brief overview of your business plan. The purpose is to tell a story, build excitement, and elicit a request for additional information and a follow-up meeting. Your slides should be simple and concise. Replace words and bullet points with images. Use each slide to tell a story rather than recite facts. Use very conservative estimates, forecasts and assumption. Keep the presentation to 20 minutes. Complement your pitch deck with additional documents, such as an Executive Summary, technical documents, financial projections and market research. When pitching your business, it is important to demonstrate high energy and excitement about your opportunity. Ensure you get feedback on both your business opportunity and on your pitch. Use the feedback and business progress to keep your deck up-to-date.</p>\n<p>These are some sample pitch decks:</p>\n<p><a href="https://pitchdeck.improvepresentation.com/best-pitch-decks" target="_blank">https://pitchdeck.improvepresentation.com/best-pitch-decks</a></p>\n<p><a href="http://bestpitchdecks.com/" target="_blank">http://bestpitchdecks.com/</a></p>\n<p>Your pitch deck should include:</p>\n<p><strong>Introduction:</strong> Summarize your vision and elevator pitch. Include a quick one sentence overview of your business and the value that you provide to your customers.</p>\n<p><strong>Team:</strong> Describe roles, responsibilities, unique and relevant experience and the reasons why your team are the right people to build and grow the company. Highlight relevant successes of key team members and their expertise. Also identify the key positions that you still need to fill and why those positions are critical to company growth.</p>\n<p><strong>Problem/Solution Fit:</strong> Summarize the problem, which should be significant, and explain how your offering solves that problem. Highlight the uniqueness of your approach.</p>\n<p><strong>Market:</strong> Quantify the Total Available Market (&ldquo;TAM&rdquo;), Serviceable Available Market (&ldquo;SAM&rdquo;), and the Serviceable Obtainable Market (&ldquo;SOM&rdquo;). For example, the TAM may be all retail sales. The SAM for your eCommerce service may be online retail sales. And your SOM maybe online retail sales for customers who are willing to wait two weeks for a purchase in order to receive a 50% discount.</p>\n<p><strong>Product and Services:</strong> Describe your offerings and clarify the advantages over alternative solutions and work arounds.</p>\n<p><strong>Business/Revenue Model:</strong> Summarize your business model and clearly show how it delivers value to all stakeholders and how it generates revenues.</p>\n<p><strong>Industry Fit:</strong> Summarize how your business fits into the industry by summarizing your position relative to the competition, distributors, suppliers, and possible new entrants. Also explain the barriers to Entry.</p>\n<p><strong>Traction, Validation and Product/Market Fit:</strong> Describe how the value provided by your product makes it a no brainer for your customers to sign up and retain your business. Describe how your sales and early adopters validate the market and your business model.</p>\n<p><strong>Marketing and Growth Strategy:</strong> Provide a roadmap that describes the milestones that you have achieved and the milestones ahead. Describe your sales plan, sales channels and your sales approach for each key market segment.</p>\n<p><strong>Strategic Relationships:</strong> Describe the strategic relationships that you already have and will need to improve your chances of success.</p>\n<p><strong>Success Metrics:</strong> Specify your success metrics or key performance indicators (&ldquo;KPIs&rdquo;). Your success metrics should quantify the business factors that reflect the health of your business model.</p>\n<p><strong>Financial Overview:</strong> Indicate the financial potential of your business and summarize your assumptions. You should also have a separate spreadsheet that allows the assumptions to be adjusted to determine their impact on projected financial performance.</p>\n<p><strong>Use of Funds:</strong> If you are seeking funds indicate how they will be used and what you will achieve.</p>\n<p><strong>Capital and Valuation:</strong> Summarize your capitalization table and expected valuation.</p>\n<p><strong>Others:</strong> You also may want to add pictures of your offerings and describe potential exit strategies.</p>\n<p><a href="https://pitchdeck.improvepresentation.com/what-is-a-pitch-deck" target="_blank">https://pitchdeck.improvepresentation.com/what-is-a-pitch-deck</a></p>\n<p><a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/chancebarnett/2014/05/09/investor-pitch-deck-to-raise-money-for-startups/#c9ea87c48631" target="">http://www.forbes.com/sites/chancebarnett/2014/05/09/investor-pitch-deck-to-raise-money-for-startups/#c9ea87c48631</a></p>\n<p>Chance Barnett: Investor Pitch Deck Template</p>\n<p>Enmetric Systems</p>\n<p>Reid Hoffman&rsquo;s LinkedIn Pitch Deck</p>\n<p>Aria Retirement Solutions</p>\n<p>Buffer</p>\n<p>Dave McClure&rsquo;s &lsquo;Startup Viagra&rsquo; Template</p>\n<p>Innovative Solar</p>\n<p>Sky Fernandes&rsquo; VC Template</p>\n<p>Go Greek Yogurt</p>\n<p>Chance Barnett advocates storytelling, such as:</p>\n<p>&ldquo;There is a huge opportunity to do X as a giant business. We&rsquo;ve cracked the code, and this is how my company is doing it and will dominate this market. Here&rsquo;s who myself and my team are, and why we&rsquo;re the only people to back in this space. It&rsquo;s working, and now we need money for X and Y to grow.&rdquo;</p>\n<p><a href="http://blog.clarity.fm/pitching-hack-its-not-what-you-said-its-how-you-made-them-feel/" target="">http://blog.clarity.fm/pitching-hack-its-not-what-you-said-its-how-you-made-them-feel/</a></p>', 'R4', '#e8a514', '160.0 CBS Pitch Deck.pdf', '160.0 Pitch Deck Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:40:15');
