(17, 'Build MVP Backend', '<p>When building the MVP backend, there are four main considerations:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Quality &ndash; Ensure the product will meet the quality expectations of your target market.</li>\r\n<li>Do not over engineer &ndash; Do not add in features or excessive quality that do not reduce risk for your target market. Conduct code reviews to ensure compliance with appropriate coding standards. Ensure the architecture, design and test results are approved and documented.</li>\r\n<li>Limitations &ndash; Do not create unnecessary limitations that will impede future growth or your ability to pivot. For example, your developers may build a solution that works well when tested with a list of 10 test customers but may be unusable for a list of 10,000 customers.</li>\r\n<li>Time-to-market &ndash; Getting to market too quickly with an un finished product may cause more harm than good. Conversely, waiting until the product is perfect may cause you to miss the opportunity window. Only build the functionality that is necessary to satisfy the early adopters so that you can learn and adjust while ensuring it meets their quality expectations.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>If you decide to contract out your development work then ensure you have a deliverable based contract. Each milestone payment should be tied to an unambiguous deliverable that has clear acceptance criteria. That acceptance criteria should include acceptance testing using test cases that you have pre-approved. Make the developer responsible for creating the test data. Testing should be conducted on your servers not in the sub-contractor&rsquo;s environment. The contract should clearly state that you own all rights to the code and any derivative products. Also, that the developer is not allowed to use any part of the code or proprietary concepts with any other client. There should also be non-disclosure and non-circumvent clauses. You should also add termination for cause and termination for convenience clauses. Some entrepreneurs like clauses that include penalties for bad performance by a supplier and incentives for good performance. You also should include a clause that prevents the developer from publicizing the contract, or you as a client, and from using your name or logo without your prior written permission.Also include a clause that makes it clear that you are independent entities and no partnership or employee relationship is implied.</p>', 'R2', '#58c517', '1485168564_682002170.0 CBS MVP Backend.pdf', '1485168564_718410170.0 MVP Backend Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:28:11'),
(18, 'User Acceptance Testing', '<p>User Acceptance Testing (&ldquo;UAT&rdquo;) is the final phase of testing your offering after unit testing, functional testing, regression testing, integration testing and system testing. It is also known as Beta, Application, or End-User Testing. The main purpose of UAT is to validate that the delivered functionality meets the business requirements before the product is released to the market. Users of the final product should participate in UAT. The data and test environment should mirror the user&rsquo;s data and infrastructure. A test plan and test cases should be approved prior to commencing the test phase. A test case is a usage scenario that specifies the sequence of steps that the tester should execute to verify that the system is working as designed. A Test Plan is a collection of test cases. It also includes an execution plan and an indication of how the set of tests cover the intended requirements. During the execution of the Test Plan, test results should be recorded and defects tracked to resolution then re-tested. The final test results should be approved by appropriate stakeholders before releasing the product to the market. While many defects are caused by defective code, some are caused by ambiguous requirements and missed requirements. Either way, oftentimes a decision has to be made to correct a defect and perhaps delay the release or fix the defect in a subsequent release. This should be documented in the final QA Acceptance report.</p>\r\n<p>UAT will also reveal if the product is easy to use, is what the user wants, and does it behave as anticipated. During UAT you look for many issues, such as performance, stability, do functions accept the correct inputs and provide the correct outputs, does system performance change with load, and does the system only consume the expected resources.</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.softwaretestinghelp.com/successful-user-acceptance-testing/" target="_blank">http://www.softwaretestinghelp.com/successful-user-acceptance-testing/</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://riceconsulting.com/home/index.php/User-Acceptance-Testing/what-is-the-value-of-user-acceptance-testing.html" target="_blank">http://riceconsulting.com/home/index.php/User-Acceptance-Testing/what-is-the-value-of-user-acceptance-testing.html</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://usersnap.com/blog/user-acceptance-testing-right/" target="_blank">http://usersnap.com/blog/user-acceptance-testing-right/</a></p>', 'R3', '#58c517', '1485168656_470981180.0 CBS UAT.pdf', '1485168656_135528180.0 UAT Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:40:40'),
(19, 'Execute Pilot', '<p>There is no point in building an incredible product that no one wants. One way to reduce costs and risks is to identify a problem, propose a solution, conduct research, build an MVP then conduct a pilot. A pilot is a controlled experiment and a dress rehearsal for launch. It must have clear goals and a well thought out execution plan. The goals should include proving a number of hypotheses for a very targeted market. For a startup, the target market will usually be the early adopters. One hypothesis could relate to the target market&rsquo;s perception of your value proposition or the target market&rsquo;s purchase decision process. For example, determine which segment of the target market would delay a purchase for two weeks for the possibility of a 50% discount. Another example, is what will influence your purchase decision more; a recommendation from a friend, expert opinion, endorsement from someone famous, a comparison of features with competitive offerings or something else.</p>\r\n<p>You should track these metrics and treat each product feature like a micro experiment. Focus on MVP features and key use cases. Measure revenue generating offerings not give aways. Focus on innovators and early adopters. Target 10 to 30 customers. Ensure you learn something that will help you penetrate each segment. Also ensure you prove or reject the key hypotheses about your business model, particularly your value proposition, distribution strategy and customer acquisition plan.</p>\r\n<p>Ensure you develop a coherent plan that will govern the execution of your pilot from start to end. The pilot should have a fixed timeline and you should ensure all required resources are lined up and understand expectations. Clearly define roles and responsibilities. Include a method to add and remove pilot users and a way to record and triage real time feedback. You should learn who to include in your initial target market and who to exclude, what they value and what may be a negative, how they make a purchase decision, how you should reach them and when, how they want to access your offering, what they perceive as the whole product and minimum feature set, which pricing models will work, and what and how they are will to pay. You should let the pilot users use your MVP and reward them for participating.</p>\r\n<p>You need the pilot users to be strong advocates of your product. Try to meet with the pilot users in person to elicit open feedback. You must be prepared to make product changes in order to demonstrate sufficient utility to compel the pilot users to rave about your product at the end of the pilot. This means you must understand what the pilot users are asking for and why. In the end, the pilot users must see and be able to articulate utility, simplicity and value. You also need testimonials, case studies and references for your investors.</p>\r\n<p><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/startup-lessons-from-running-pilot-program-shreesha-ramdas" target="_blank">https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/startup-lessons-from-running-pilot-program-shreesha-ramdas</a></p>', 'R1', '#e8a514', '1485168786_363955190.0 CBS Pilot.pdf', '1485168786_578142190.0 Pilot Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:28:37'),
(20, 'Pivot/Optimize MVP & Business Model', '<p>Based on the results of the pilot you should decide:</p>\r\n<p>1. Whether to exit.</p>\r\n<p>2. Whether to pivot your offering, your target market or both.</p>\r\n<p>3. Whether to make minor adjustments to your offering and business model then proceed.</p>', 'R4', '#e8a514', '1485168843_490578200.0 CBS Pivot Blank.pdf', '1485168843_455228200.0 Pivot Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:41:15'),
