ip reputation in your industry. You can then execute a highly targeted speaking and media briefing program.</p>\r\n<p>According to Balaji Viswanathan, your launch strategy should include the following:</p>\r\n<p><a href="https://www.quora.com/How-do-you-successfully-launch-a-product/answer/Balaji-Viswanathan-2?srid=CRHx" target="_blank">https://www.quora.com/How-do-you-successfully-launch-a-product/answer/Balaji-Viswanathan-2?srid=CRHx</a></p>\r\n<p>Six months before your launch you should post content on twitter and other social media platforms, get active on forums, setup you blog, and sign up a few influential customers to participate in UAT.</p>\r\n<p>Three months before launch cultivate relationships with bloggers and start attending related events. Also list your startup on Angel List, StartupLi.st CrunchBase and Listio.</p>\r\n<p>One week before launch build a great landing page, optimize your app and website, fine tune your SEO, use social monitoring tools, write a press release, setup your Facebook page, create viral content with emotive stories, create interesting infographics, create fun contests, write to bloggers, prepare a video demo, and create a presentation that summarizes the problem, solution, benefits and advantages.</p>\r\n<p>On your launch day, post to your blog your presentation, videos and testimonials from UAT testers. Tweet, post on Facebook, send emails, with a call to action. Post your site in killerstartups, hackernews and similar web sites. Monitor social media and your site&rsquo;s metrics. Respond to queries as soon as possible.</p>\r\n<p>After the launch, thank bloggers and others who covered you. Engage customers on social media. Fix bugs and develop a roadmap for new features. Write &ldquo;how to&rdquo; tutorials and leverage opportunities to demo your product.</p>\r\n<p><img src="../../../images/setup-operation1.jpg" alt="" width="420" height="452" /></p>\r\n<p>Source: RocketWatcher.com</p>\r\n<p><a href="https://blog.gleam.io/prelaunch/" target="_blank">https://blog.gleam.io/prelaunch/</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://venturebeat.com/2013/06/05/the-ultimate-guide-to-startup-pre-launch-marketing-in-5-simple-steps/" target="_blank">http://venturebeat.com/2013/06/05/the-ultimate-guide-to-startup-pre-launch-marketing-in-5-simple-steps/</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="https://foundrmag.com/pr-checklist-for-startups-15-things-to-do-before-your-product-launch/" target="_blank">https://foundrmag.com/pr-checklist-for-startups-15-things-to-do-before-your-product-launch/</a></p>', 'R1', '#e8a514', '1485169085_886479230.0 CBS Launch Blank.pdf', '1485169085_977034230.0 Launch Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:29:28'),
(24, 'Execute Growth Strategy', '<p>According to Wikipedia, customer acquisition management is a set of methodologies and systems used to manage customer prospects and customer inquiries generated by a variety of marketing techniques. This facilitates the acquisition of targeted customers in an effective fashion.</p>\r\n<p>According to help Scout, acquiring new customers means understanding what makes your customers tick and investing heavily in inbound marketing strategies such as content, building an email newsletter and search engine optimization (SEO). Inbound marketing pulls customers in using great content that attracts qualified visitors for the life of your startup. Conversely, outbound marketing requires continuous spending to attract new visitors.</p>\r\n<p><a href="https://www.helpscout.net/customer-acquisition/" target="_blank">https://www.helpscout.net/customer-acquisition/</a></p>\r\n<p>The point is that a great product alone is not enough for you to succeed. Conversely, no amount of marketing can make a bad product succeed. Your success demands a great product and great marketing.</p>\r\n<p><img src="../../../images/aquui.jpg" alt="" /></p>\r\n<p>Dave McClure, founder of the Silicon Valley Accelerator &ldquo;500 Startups&rdquo;, designed a customer acquisition strategy termed AARRR &ndash; Acquisition, Activation, Revenue, Retention, Referral. This is a blueprint for hypergrowth.</p>\r\n<p><img src="../../../images/aqqui2.jpg" alt="" /></p>\r\n<p>Source: Startitup &ndash; http://startitup.co/guides/374/aarrr-startup-metrics</p>\r\n<p>A successful startup will measure, analyze and optimize each of these 5 metrics.</p>\r\n<p><strong>StartitUp Website Case Study:</strong> StartitUp is getting 1000 visitors/month (Acquisition), and their Activation (conversion) is 70%, so they are activating about 700 users/month. Only 20% of those users return after their first visit (Retention). Out of those 20% (140 users), only 10% are paying customers (Revenue), so only 14 users pay each month. Out of the 700 users who activate per month, about 10% refer the service to their friends (Referral).</p>\r\n<p>Acquisition is your baseline statistic which you can improve by adding more channels and optimizing SEO. In the case study above, Activation (conversion) is high (70%) but Retention is low (20%). You can improve Retention by adding enduring features that add value over time, such as by providing an evolving knowledgebase that customers value and augment. In the case study above, customer monetization (revenue) is also low (10%). You can improve revenue by increasing your product&rsquo;s value/price ratio. One method is to add value to your product bundles or you can discount your pricing plan. In addition, you can improve the referral rate (10%) by adding social sharing features.</p>\r\n<p>Your MVP pilot should focus on optimizing activation and retention. You can optimize acquisition and referral later when testing your growth hacking hypotheses.</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.slideshare.net/dmc500hats/startup-metrics-for-pirates-long-version" target="_blank">http://www.slideshare.net/dmc500hats/startup-metrics-for-pirates-long-version</a></p>\r\n<p>Lean Analytics: http://www.kaushik.net/avinash/lean-analytics-cycle-metrics-hypothesis-experiment-act/ Customer acquisition</p>\r\n<p>Paid media Marketing includes display (Facebook), search (Google) and affiliate options. Facebook is a great customer acquisition channel if you want to run a highly targeted campaign. Google is a great channel if you provide a solution that your prospects are searching for. Google will also sell you banner ads that will appear on 3rd party websites. They allow you to specify the target 3rd party websites and key words. Google remarketing uses information about one web site that you have visited to inform ads on the next web site you visit. Facebook Exchange also displays ads about websites that you have recently visited. LinkedIn allows you to target ads by job title and industry sector.</p>\r\n<p>According to Jason Baptiste, startups should consider the following 16 channels for customer acquisition:</p>\r\n<p>1. PR &ndash; Can be low cost and targeted</p>\r\n<p>2. Organic Search &ndash; Can be low cost but requires SEO</p>\r\n<p>3. Content Marketing &ndash; Includes educational, useful, analytical and actionable blog posts. Also infographics and white papers can be powerful generators of leads.</p>\r\n<p>4. Affiliate Programs</p>\r\n<p>5. Lead generation programs &ndash; pay for qualified leads</p>\r\n<p>6. Events and Conferences &ndash; Gather direct interactive feedback and educate</p>\r\n<p>7. 3rd Party Social Media Platforms &ndash; Apps and pages inside social networks.</p>\r\n<p>8. Social Media Marketing &ndash; Permission based marketing</p>\r\n<p>9. Mobile Platform Distribution &ndash; Apple, Android and mobile web</p>\r\n<p>10. APIs &ndash; Integration with other complementary offerings.</p>\r\n<p>11. Paid Online Advertising &ndash; Must track conversion rates, highly targeted, track life time value and acquisition cost</p>\r\n<p>12. Direct Sales &ndash; More important for enterprise and B2B sales</p>\r\n<p>13. Business Development &ndash; Partner with same customer base then cross sell or up sell</p>\r\n<p>14. Referral Programs &ndash; Encourage customers to attract other customers</p>\r\n<p>15. Traditional Media &ndash; Useful to reach the early and late majority. Has large upfront cost with poor analytics.</p>\r\n<p>16. New products and add-ons to existing customers &ndash; Complementary offerings and Product line extension. You should determine how much, time effort and money to devote to each of these channels. You should also measure your customer acquisition cost and how it is changing over time.</p>\r\n<p>According to Venture Harbor, the foundations of an aggressive marketing strategy are:</p>\r\n<p>Growth Hacking &ndash; building marketing into the product.</p>\r\n<p>Conversion rate optimization (&ldquo;CRO&rdquo;).</p>\r\n<p>Using Facebook ads to understand customers.</p>\r\n<p>Customer feedback loops.</p>\r\n<p>Diffusion of innovation and targeting early adopters.</p>\r\n<p>Fine tuning your messaging.</p>\r\n<p>Differentiation.</p>\r\n<p>a) Growth Hacking</p>\r\n<p>Your offering should incentivize each user to refer other users and the referral process should be simple to use. This referral functionality should be built into your offering to encourage referrals whenever the user is inspired to do so by your offering. This strategy is one form of growth hacking. The key metric is the viral coefficient which is the number of new users generated by each existing user. A viral coefficient of 1 means each existing user will attract one new user. A viral coefficient that exceeds 1.1 will drive exponential growth. During primary market research you can ask how likely each surveyed customer is to recommend your product. If the aggregate Net Promote score is greater than 9.0 then exponential growth is possible.</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://techcrunch.com/2009/10/18/ps-i-love-you-get-your-free-email-at-hotmail/" target="_blank">http://techcrunch.com/2009/10/18/ps-i-love-you-get-your-free-email-at-hotmail/</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://thenextweb.com/eu/2013/05/05/how-eventbrite-built-a-company-culture-that-scales-with-co-founder-julia-hartz-video/" target="_blank">http://thenextweb.com/eu/2013/05/05/how-eventbrite-built-a-company-culture-that-scales-with-co-founder-julia-hartz-video/</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="https://www.quora.com/How-effective-is-Dropboxs-referral-program-at-bringing-in-*paying*-users-i-e-how-many-subscribers-do-they-have" target="_blank">https://www.quora.com/How-effective-is-Dropboxs-referral-program-at-bringing-in-*paying*-users-i-e-how-many-subscribers-do-they-have</a></p>\r\n<p>b) Conversion Rate Optimization (CRO)</p>\r\n<p>To optimize conversation rates, you must understand why some visitors convert into customers while others do not convert. You must then improve your message or value proposition. For example, you can overcome objections by creating urgency, such as only 2 widgets remaining. You can also improve conversation rates by changing the layout or presentation of information on your landing page. You should also use A/B testing to compare the conversion rate of different approaches.</p>\r\n<p>c) Social Media</p>\r\n<p>Facebook enables you to run highly targeted campaigns that can track conversion rates for very specific demographic or psychographic target segments. This will enable you to quickly confirm your target audience and their acquisition cost. If you use SEO with Google, you are helping prospects find what they are looking for. When you use social media sites, you are distracting prospects from their primary mission.</p>\r\n<p>d) Customer Feedback Loops</p>\r\n<p>A feedback loop is a process that enables you to gather feedback from customers, learn from that feedback then change your offering in response to the feedback. This process enables you to build, learn, and adjust. Feedback loops will help you increase customer satisfaction, which can drive business growth. Surveys are the most common way to elicit feedback from customers.</p>\r\n<p>e) Diffusion of innovation</p>\r\n<p>A mass market strategy will not work for most startups because the early majority will resist change that has not been validated by early adopters. Instead of using limited resources to build an initial offering that satisfies the lowest common denominator of the mass market, you should build a targeted solution that exceeds the expectations of an attractive and influential niche. Your initial launch strategy and messaging should excite innovators and early adopters. Then you must adjust your offering, based on their feedback, to exceed their expectations, obtain their validation then leverage their advocacy to target the next niche.</p>\r\n<p>f) Fine Tune Your Messaging</p>\r\n<p>Explain the pain points that your startup addresses and why your customers should buy your offering. This will enable them to understand your value proposition and then convert.</p>\r\n<p>g) Differentiation</p>\r\n<p>Today, the average person sees 1,000 to 5,000 advertisements per day. Your offering must be very different to stand out, so it can be recognized. You should read Edward De Bono&rsquo;s book on lateral thinking then do something remarkable to get remarked upon. One way to stand out is to give before you take. Content marketing is an effective way to do this. For example, if you give content that is highly valued by your target audience, then you can receive instant credibility. This credibility affords you influence over your target audience which you can leverage to drive customer acquisition.</p>\r\n<p>In general, you want an offering that has the potential for high viral growth and high retention. Viral growth requires an offering that is:</p>\r\n<p>Easy to Access</p>\r\n<p>A no brainer in terms of total utility V total cost to use</p>\r\n<p>Easy to validate its utility using small tests</p>\r\n<p>Recommended by an enthusiastic stream of early adopters</p>\r\n<p>Easy for customers to understand and explain</p>\r\n<p>Blessed with a significant advantage which is usually the first mover advantage for startups</p>\r\n<p>High retention can be realized by:</p>\r\n<p>High network effects</p>\r\n<p>High barriers to entry and exit</p>\r\n<p>A differentiated user experience</p>\r\n<p>Earned Media</p>\r\n<p>Earned Media is publicity generated by advocates, such as customers, fans and partners. It is difficult to cultivate and measure but it can be the most cost effective and credible media option for startups. Owned Media Marketing</p>\r\n<p>Owned Media Marketing refers to channels that you own, such as your website and social media profiles. You can increase their effectiveness by writing about what your customers want to hear and by using your owned media as a landing page that increases the effectiveness of your paid and earned media campaigns.</p>\r\n<p>Your Hypothesis</p>\r\n<p>Figure out a critical business metric to improve. For example, if the metric is the number of people buying, the metric is conversion rate. If it is the number of referrals sent by customers, it''s virality. If it''s the number of paying users who quit, it''s churn. Then specify a success target for each target metric. Form a hypothesis which is an educated guess that proposes a solution based on evidence. For example, if I offer a 75% discount then more than 20% customers will wait more than two weeks for a deal. You can design experiments around pricing, features, distribution, positioning, customer acquisition, rewards, bundling, etc. Do some research to figure out possible customer objections to overcome or conversion strategies that have been successful for other competitors. Your hypotheses could prove the effectiveness of specific strategies to overcome customer objections or prove that successful conversion strategies from other industries will work for your business model or even determine why loyal customers do not churn. The point is that you should develop a hypothesis, test its validity then adjust.</p>\r\n<p><img src="../../../images/aqqui3.jpg" alt="" /></p>\r\n<p>Source: http://500hats.typepad.com/500blogs/2007/09/startup-metrics.html</p>\r\n<p>Finally, according to Woody Allen, 80% of success is showing up. Go where you know your influencers will be. A conference, a meetup, or a book signing whatever is cost effective.</p>\r\n<p><a href="https://www.ventureharbour.com/ultimate-startup-marketing-strategy/" target="_blank">https://www.ventureharbour.com/ultimate-startup-marketing-strategy/</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://jasonlbaptiste.com/startups/distribution-distribution-distribution/" target="_blank">http://jasonlbaptiste.com/startups/distribution-distribution-distribution/</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.theequitykicker.com/2010/10/13/a-checklist-of-distribution-channels-for-startups/" target="_blank">http://www.theequitykicker.com/2010/10/13/a-checklist-of-distribution-channels-for-startups/</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/20140911153505-382127-how-to-design-your-startup-distribution-strategy-in-4-steps" target="_blank">https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/20140911153505-382127-how-to-design-your-startup-distribution-strategy-in-4-steps</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://quibb.com/links/how-to-build-a-distribution-first-startup" target="_blank">http://quibb.com/links/how-to-build-a-distribution-first-startup</a></p>', 'R4', '#e8a514', '1485169244_622863240.0 CBS Growth Blank.pdf', '1485169244_177560220.0 Launch Strategy Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:41:50');
