nvert. You must then improve your message or value proposition. For example, you can overcome objections by creating urgency, such as only 2 widgets remaining. You can also improve conversation rates by changing the layout or presentation of information on your landing page. You should also use A/B testing to compare the conversion rate of different approaches.</p>\r\n<p>c) Social Media</p>\r\n<p>Facebook enables you to run highly targeted campaigns that can track conversion rates for very specific demographic or psychographic target segments. This will enable you to quickly confirm your target audience and their acquisition cost. If you use SEO with Google, you are helping prospects find what they are looking for. When you use social media sites, you are distracting prospects from their primary mission.</p>\r\n<p>d) Customer Feedback Loops</p>\r\n<p>A feedback loop is a process that enables you to gather feedback from customers, learn from that feedback then change your offering in response to the feedback. This process enables you to build, learn, and adjust. Feedback loops will help you increase customer satisfaction, which can drive business growth. Surveys are the most common way to elicit feedback from customers.</p>\r\n<p>e) Diffusion of innovation</p>\r\n<p>A mass market strategy will not work for most startups because the early majority will resist change that has not been validated by early adopters. Instead of using limited resources to build an initial offering that satisfies the lowest common denominator of the mass market, you should build a targeted solution that exceeds the expectations of an attractive and influential niche. Your initial launch strategy and messaging should excite innovators and early adopters. Then you must adjust your offering, based on their feedback, to exceed their expectations, obtain their validation then leverage their advocacy to target the next niche.</p>\r\n<p>f) Fine Tune Your Messaging</p>\r\n<p>Explain the pain points that your startup addresses and why your customers should buy your offering. This will enable them to understand your value proposition and then convert.</p>\r\n<p>g) Differentiation</p>\r\n<p>Today, the average person sees 1,000 to 5,000 advertisements per day. Your offering must be very different to stand out, so it can be recognized. You should read Edward De Bono&rsquo;s book on lateral thinking then do something remarkable to get remarked upon. One way to stand out is to give before you take. Content marketing is an effective way to do this. For example, if you give content that is highly valued by your target audience, then you can receive instant credibility. This credibility affords you influence over your target audience which you can leverage to drive customer acquisition.</p>\r\n<p>In general, you want an offering that has the potential for high viral growth and high retention. Viral growth requires an offering that is:</p>\r\n<p>Easy to Access</p>\r\n<p>A no brainer in terms of total utility V total cost to use</p>\r\n<p>Easy to validate its utility using small tests</p>\r\n<p>Recommended by an enthusiastic stream of early adopters</p>\r\n<p>Easy for customers to understand and explain</p>\r\n<p>Blessed with a significant advantage which is usually the first mover advantage for startups</p>\r\n<p>High retention can be realized by:</p>\r\n<p>High network effects</p>\r\n<p>High barriers to entry and exit</p>\r\n<p>A differentiated user experience</p>\r\n<p>Earned Media</p>\r\n<p>Earned Media is publicity generated by advocates, such as customers, fans and partners. It is difficult to cultivate and measure but it can be the most cost effective and credible media option for startups. Owned Media Marketing</p>\r\n<p>Owned Media Marketing refers to channels that you own, such as your website and social media profiles. You can increase their effectiveness by writing about what your customers want to hear and by using your owned media as a landing page that increases the effectiveness of your paid and earned media campaigns.</p>\r\n<p>Your Hypothesis</p>\r\n<p>Figure out a critical business metric to improve. For example, if the metric is the number of people buying, the metric is conversion rate. If it is the number of referrals sent by customers, it''s virality. If it''s the number of paying users who quit, it''s churn. Then specify a success target for each target metric. Form a hypothesis which is an educated guess that proposes a solution based on evidence. For example, if I offer a 75% discount then more than 20% customers will wait more than two weeks for a deal. You can design experiments around pricing, features, distribution, positioning, customer acquisition, rewards, bundling, etc. Do some research to figure out possible customer objections to overcome or conversion strategies that have been successful for other competitors. Your hypotheses could prove the effectiveness of specific strategies to overcome customer objections or prove that successful conversion strategies from other industries will work for your business model or even determine why loyal customers do not churn. The point is that you should develop a hypothesis, test its validity then adjust.</p>\r\n<p><img src="../../../images/aqqui3.jpg" alt="" /></p>\r\n<p>Source: http://500hats.typepad.com/500blogs/2007/09/startup-metrics.html</p>\r\n<p>Finally, according to Woody Allen, 80% of success is showing up. Go where you know your influencers will be. A conference, a meetup, or a book signing whatever is cost effective.</p>\r\n<p><a href="https://www.ventureharbour.com/ultimate-startup-marketing-strategy/" target="_blank">https://www.ventureharbour.com/ultimate-startup-marketing-strategy/</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://jasonlbaptiste.com/startups/distribution-distribution-distribution/" target="_blank">http://jasonlbaptiste.com/startups/distribution-distribution-distribution/</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.theequitykicker.com/2010/10/13/a-checklist-of-distribution-channels-for-startups/" target="_blank">http://www.theequitykicker.com/2010/10/13/a-checklist-of-distribution-channels-for-startups/</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/20140911153505-382127-how-to-design-your-startup-distribution-strategy-in-4-steps" target="_blank">https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/20140911153505-382127-how-to-design-your-startup-distribution-strategy-in-4-steps</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://quibb.com/links/how-to-build-a-distribution-first-startup" target="_blank">http://quibb.com/links/how-to-build-a-distribution-first-startup</a></p>', 'R2', '#58c517', '1485169391_175783250.0 CBS Optimize Blank.pdf', '1485169391_49618250.0 Optimize Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:29:45'),
(26, 'Series A Investment', '<p><a target="_blank">https://www.quora.com/What-are-some-key-signs-i-e-milestones-achieved-that-a-startup-might-be-ready-to-start-approaching-VC-firms-to-raise-a-Series-A-round</a></p>\r\n<p><a target="_blank">https://equityzen.com/blog/metrics-required-for-series-a/?utm_source=Quora&amp;utm_medium=SBresponse&amp;utm_content=SeriesAMetrics&amp;utm_campaign=BlogPost</a></p>\r\n<p>There are many micro Seed VC funds, Angels, Accelerators and other resources available for a seed round. AngelList and SeedInvest are useful resources. However, for a Series A investment, the due diligence and expected metrics are an order of magnitude higher.</p>\r\n<p><a target="_blank">http://mashable.com/2013/05/06/startup-venture-capital/#2MWyWgU6juqq</a></p>\r\n<p><a target="_blank">http://www.garage.com/resources/critical-factors-for-obtaining-venture-funding/</a></p>\r\n<p>According to Shriram Bhashyam, you should achieve the following to be ready for Series A funding:</p>\r\n<p>Traction in a large market</p>\r\n<p>Scalable marketing channels (e.g., do no max out at low volumes)</p>\r\n<p>Significant margins</p>\r\n<p>Detailed knowledge of customer acquisition cost and customer lifetime value</p>\r\n<p>$1M in monthly recurring revenue (MRR) for eCommerce</p>\r\n<p>50k active daily users and 25% month-to-month growth for apps</p>\r\n<p>$50k to $150k MRR, $1.5M ARR and 100% year-on-year growth for SaaS</p>\r\n<p>For markets, $0.5M to $1M in monthly gross market volume (GMV) and 20% to 30% MoM growth in GMV.</p>\r\n<p>Liquidity: &gt; 10% demand/supply ratio (e.g., demand exceeds 10% of supply).</p>\r\n<p>According to Raad Ahmed, the following table is representative of the dilution that you can expect through a Series A investment.</p>\r\n<p><img src="../../../images/series.png" alt="" width="420" height="452" /></p>\r\n<p>If you believe your startup qualifies for a VC investment and you want to proceed then find a list of VCs that focus on your industry and your investment stage. Your research should also identify a VC partner whose area of interest is a good match to your startup. The following article from Mark Suster, indicates what he would look for in a VC.</p>\r\n<p><a target="_blank">https://bothsidesofthetable.com/what-i-would-look-for-when-choosing-a-vc-knowing-what-i-know-now-fbdc67689449#.1jbnpl8st</a></p>\r\n<p>After you obtain your short list of VCs, you should use your network to get an introduction. Then you need to polish your pitch deck, business plan, executive summary, demo, standalone handout and business cards.</p>\r\n<p>According to Ben Yoskovitz, your Executive Summary should cover the following:</p>\r\n<p><a target="_blank">http://www.instigatorblog.com/8-investor-questions/2011/03/14/</a></p>\r\n<p>Current status: funds raised to-date, monthly budget, revenue, team size, team expertise, customers, metrics Problem you&rsquo;re solving</p>\r\n<p>Market size &amp; potential</p>\r\n<p>Solution</p>\r\n<p>Competition</p>\r\n<p>Go to market strategy</p>\r\n<p>Unfair advantage</p>\r\n<p>The ask (how much you want to raise &amp; why)</p>\r\n<p><a target="_blank">http://www.instigatorblog.com/8-tips-for-successful-venture-capital-meetings/2008/12/09/</a></p>\r\n<p>In the article above, Ben Yoskovitz states that the pitch is what a venture capitalist uses to size you up. Most often it&rsquo;s the CEO giving the pitch and they&rsquo;re looking for personality, confidence, passion, knowledge, intelligence and more. They&rsquo;re gauging &ndash; without really listening to every detail of what you&rsquo;re saying &ndash; whether or not they think you can lead your startup to success.</p>\r\n<p>In his TED talk, David Rose says VCs are looking for Integrity, passion, experience, knowledge, skills, leadership, commitment, vision, realism, and coachability. He adds that your presentation should include your logo, business overview, team, market, product, business model, relationships, competition, barriers to entry, financial overview, use of funds, capital structure and valuation. Your offering requires third party validation and the promise of a tremendous upside.</p>\r\n<p><a target="_blank">https://www.ted.com/talks/david_s_rose_on_pitching_to_vcs?language=en</a></p>\r\n<p>If your VC selection process, preparation and pitch are perfect then you still may not finalize an investment. According to Paul Graham, (http://paulgraham.com/startupfunding.html), birds fly; fish swim; and deals fall through. The reason is that venture capital is such a risky environment. People about to fund or acquire a startup are prone to wicked cases of buyer''s remorse. They don''t really grasp the risk they''re taking till the deal''s about to close. And then they panic.</p>\r\n<p>Conversely, if all goes well, an interested VC will offer you a term sheet which is a summary of what the deal terms will be when and if they do a deal; lawyers will fill in the details later. By accepting the term sheet, the startup agrees to turn away other VCs for some set amount of time while this firm does the "due diligence" required for the deal. For example, the terms may be a $2 million investment at a pre-money valuation of $4 million, meaning that after the deal closes the VCs will own a third of the company (2 / (4 + 2)). The funds may be delivered in tranches based on meeting specified milestones. The founders may be required to vest their shares over four years, and the board is likely to be reconstituted to consist of two VCs, two founders, and a fifth person acceptable to both.</p>\r\n<p>Ensure you do not meet a venture capitalist without knowing who they are and knowing more about the firm they work for. You want to know the firm&rsquo;s past investment history. You want to know the history of the individuals you&rsquo;re meeting. And you want to know if they&rsquo;ve invested in anything (past or present) that&rsquo;s relevant to what you do.</p>\r\n<p>Other useful links</p>\r\n<p>https://youtu.be/8GIbCg8NpBw</p>\r\n<p>https://youtu.be/QoAOzMTLP5s</p>\r\n<p>https://youtu.be/5sn7pZXY5b4</p>\r\n<p>http://www.inc.com/magazine/201110/eric-ries-usability-testing-product-development.html</p>\r\n<p>http://theleanstartup.com/</p>\r\n<p>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lean_startup</p>\r\n<p>https://leanstack.com/why-lean-canvas/</p>', 'R3', '#58c517', '1485169506_967366260.0 CBS Series A Blank.pdf', '1485169506_693494260.0 Series A Template.pdf', 1, '2016-09-08 06:42:15');
